### Redirect Target: [Online algorithm](/Online_algorithm)

For those who enjoy efficiency, or perhaps the existential dread of real-time processing, this [redirect](/Wikipedia:Redirect) guides you to the article on [Online algorithms](/Online_algorithm). An [online algorithm](/Online_algorithm), in its essence, is a method of computation that processes its input piece by piece, as it arrives, without having the entire input available from the outset. It's a stark contrast to an [offline algorithm](/Offline_algorithm), which demands all data before it can even begin to deliberate. Imagine making life-altering decisions based solely on the last five seconds of information, with no foresight into what the next five might bring. That, in a nutshell, is the thrilling, chaotic existence of an [online algorithm](/Online_algorithm). They are crucial in scenarios where data streams continuously, such as network routing, financial trading, or dynamic resource allocation. The challenge, of course, lies in making locally optimal choices that don't lead to globally catastrophic outcomes, a struggle many humans find relatable, albeit less mathematically rigorous. The effectiveness of an [online algorithm](/Online_algorithm) is often measured by its [competitive ratio](/Competitive_ratio), comparing its performance to that of an optimal [offline algorithm](/Offline_algorithm) that had the luxury of perfect foresight—a comparison that often highlights the inherent limitations of operating in the dark.

